AGI -&nbsp;"The Region does its part and cancels tariff increases" which would bring the integrated ticket Bit per bus and meter from 1.5 to 2 euro: it is the appeal of the Capitol councillors of the Democratic Party Giovanni Zannola and Valeria Baglio, respectively president of the Mobility and group leader of the dems in Campidoglio, after the anticipations on a possible retouch of the price that would enter into force in July. "It is necessary to avoid the increase of the Bit for the Romans", the two dem exponents say, "the forecast of a tariff increase is wrong and would risk producing a boomerang effect, with more evasion and a lower recourse to public transport, penalizing the sustainability of service and environmental. The Region, which sets the tariffs of the Tpl, be clear and say if you intend to proceed with the increases for Romans and Romans". In the past the Region has provided extraordinary funds to prevent increases.
&nbsp;
"Rome, also thanks to the intense commitment of the Junta, is intervening massively with a work of substitution of the old metro tracks, the modernization and construction of new stations, which however are entailing unavoidable discomfort, such as the early closure of the service during the week or the temporary stop at some stations to make them more beautiful and functional for the Romans and in view of the Jubilee," Zannola and Baglio recalled. "Ask citizens, now or in the coming months, to pay a greater cost for a service that must still be upgraded, which must still recover thousands of miles lost in the past management, would be incomprehensible and unjustified," they added.
<br> "In the past few weeks we have indicated alternatives, such as the possible differentiation between the cost reserved for residents and commuters and that of tourist cards, which unfortunately do not seem to have been heard," said the two exponents dem.
&nbsp;
"As a Democrat Party we have also relaunched the government's request to increase the National Transport Fund and to renounce it according to the specific characteristics of the cities, considering that Rome by extension, by number of passengers transported and by number of employees far exceeds all other Italian cities. We will continue this battle. We are on the eve of the Jubilee, an extraordinary event that will call back to Rome millions of pilgrims, and bringing the cost of the ticket to 2 euros would not be a nice business card. Government and Region really want all this?", conclude.&nbsp;

